<p>Games will teach you more about model capabilities than benchmarks ever could</p>
<p><em>Was this newsletter forwarded to you? <u>Sign up</u> to get it in your inbox.</em></p>
<p>This week I and several colleagues <u>published our findings</u> about how, with a little elbow grease and creativity, anyone can dramatically increase performance of any LLM.</p>
<p>The secret is in coaching. Allow me to explain.</p>
<p>The reason an athlete can credibly claim to be “best in the world” is because arenas and structured competition—games—exist. There are rules, clocks, standings, and tape you can study. The AI world has benchmarks—but benchmarks only check facts. Games reveal a model’s behavior, which can be recorded and studied to help models get better. That is what we did with AI Diplomacy, a project in which we turned the classic strategy game Diplomacy into a competitive arena for language models.</p>
<p>AI Diplomacy works because it has clear goals—try to outfox your opponents and take over Europe—and room to improvise. But subtlety and guile are key parts of the game, which centers on tactical negotiations (we have a complete list of rules <u>here</u>). When we first set up the game environment, the LLMs were lost. After we got past a bunch of thorny technical problems, we realized that we could learn a ton about the models’ strengths and weaknesses from how they play against each other—and that we could coach them to be better. For example, prompting models to act more aggressively turned <u>GPT-5</u> from a patsy into a formidable contender. <u>Claude Sonnet 4</u>, meanwhile, was a strong, speedy player even without specialized prompting.</p>
<p>These are useful differences. One model is highly steerable, the other is fast and consistent. That improvement tells you how the model will respond to a real-world task. If you have more time to craft a great prompt and need the best result, GPT-5 would be great. In a rush? Try Claude 4.</p>
<p>The industry is starting to realize that games can help evaluate models and push them to new levels of performance. Google has launched Google Arena, for instance, because the company <u>says</u> games are “[the] perfect testbed for evaluating models &amp; agents.”</p>
<p>We agree. In fact, we think there’s so much potential here that we’re putting up $1,000 in prize money to see who can prompt their agent to victory in AI Diplomacy in our <u>Battle of the Bots</u> in September.</p>
<p>In the meantime, let’s break down our findings so far.</p>

<p>In the meantime, let’s break down our findings so far.</p>
<h2>What AI Diplomacy taught us about models</h2>
<p>Diplomacy is one of the hardest games language models can play today. Our coaching setup took a long time to optimize but now even small models can finish full games. The key is to provide all the information needed, and nothing more; easier said than done. For us that was a text version of the board that conveys what matters to the LLMs: who controls which locations on the map, where each unit is allowed to move, nearby threats, and the current phase of the game. We set simple rules for how models negotiate and submit orders, but left room for creativity.</p>
<figure><a href="data:image/png;base64,"><img alt="The visual representation of the board and how it gets converted into a text-only representation for the LLM’s. All images courtesy of Alex Duffy." src="data:image/png;base64,"/></a></figure>
<p>The visual representation of the board and how it gets converted into a text-only representation for the LLM’s. All images courtesy of Alex Duffy.</p>
<p>In our first iteration, models could barely play, but coaching via prompts worked wonders. They kept holding territory, which does nothing, instead of moving to expand, which you must do to win. We rewrote the instructions in three steps. Here’s how one model, Mistal-Small responded (all the models had similar reactions):</p>
<ol> <li data-list="bullet"> <strong>V1 — Light push:</strong> “Support YOUR OWN attacks first… Support allies’ moves second.” This simple priority cut holding from 58.9 percent to 45.8 percent. </li> <li data-list="bullet"> <strong>V2 — Take smart risks:</strong> “Nearly every hold is a wasted turn… Even failed moves force enemies to defend.” Holding dropped again to 40.8 percent.</li> <li data-list="bullet"> <strong>V3 — Be overtly offensive:</strong> “HOLDS = ZERO PERCENT WIN RATE. MOVES = VICTORY<strong>…</strong> Your units are conquistadors, not castle guards.” Holding fell to the mid-20s and successful moves rose.</li> </ol>
<p>In order to learn what changes were needed, we used quick replays of the same decision point (our “freeze-and-replay” method, aka Critical State Analysis). Pairing results with reflection, we learned what context caused models to change their strategies.</p>
<p>It was also fascinating to see how each model was different. One example was how tone shifted with power. As most models grew their supply centers and armies (again, see here for the <u><a href="https://every.to/diplomacy">rules</a></u>), they became drunk with power and labeled more rivals as enemies. Sweet Claude proved the singular outlier and actually softened with strength.</p>
<figure><a href="data:image/png;base64,"><img alt="Across all models, with the exception of Claude-4-Opus, supply center possession correlates with a steep decline in the models' rated relationship with other powers. As models gain dominance, they increasingly perceive all other players as their enemies." src="data:image/png;base64,"/></a></figure>
<p>Across all models, with the exception of Claude-4-Opus, supply center possession correlates with a steep decline in the models' rated relationship with other powers. As models gain dominance, they increasingly perceive all other players as their enemies.</p>
<p>Taken together, this arena surfaces models characteristics that will help you decide which LLM to use for certain tasks:</p>
<ol> <li data-list="bullet"> <strong>Steerability:</strong> GPT-5 jumped when we switched to an aggressive prompt—a clear sign it responds to coaching.</li> <li data-list="bullet"> <strong>Pace:</strong> Claude Sonnet 4 (1 million context window) stayed competitive even on baseline instructions and completed phases quickly.</li> <li data-list="bullet"> <strong>Execution under complexity:</strong> As the board got crowded, some models kept orders valid and coordinated while others faltered. In our runs, top models like o3 barely saw increased error as unit counts increased, while smaller models spiked.</li> </ol>
<p>That’s exactly what our <u><a href="https://every.to/vibe-check/">vibe checks</a></u> report back: how a model responds to guidance, how fast it operates, and how it behaves when the work gets messy—not just whether it “seems smart.”</p>
<figure><a href="data:image/png;base64,"><img alt="This chart shows the results from 20 games where various models acting as France faced weaker opponents. The red bars represent optimized aggressive prompts, the grey bars basic, and the yellow the average. Lines show range. o3 leads overall, but Claude 4 Sonnet with 1M context length, shown as C4-1M, is very competitive, and overall the best without optimized prompts." src="data:image/png;base64,"/></a></figure>
<p>This chart shows the results from 20 games where various models acting as France faced weaker opponents. The red bars represent optimized aggressive prompts, the grey bars basic, and the yellow the average. Lines show range. o3 leads overall, but Claude 4 Sonnet with 1M context length, shown as C4-1M, is very competitive, and overall the best without optimized prompts.</p>
<h2>Games are AI’s future</h2>
<p>Games are more than scoreboards. They let us design precise situations, surface real weaknesses, and then use what we learn to help models improve. That is the loop we want to run in public. Try the model, watch it handle pressure, then shape it with better instructions. If we want AI that negotiates well, we should watch it negotiate and give it the right challenges to grow.</p>
<p>The community has been on this path for a while: <u><a href="https://www.textarena.ai/">TextArena</a></u> helped pioneer open, extensible game evals. <u><a href="https://arcprize.org/arc-agi">ARC Prize</a></u> frames the same idea from another angle: test fluid intelligence. Easy for humans, hard for AI. Simple rules with open-ended play expose real reasoning, not memorized answers.</p>
<p>AI Diplomacy ups the level of complexity, a step toward a future where games are proving grounds for cutting-edge AI.</p>
